    </span>

    
      &middot;
      <a class="smallText greyText" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link244340427" title="Flag this comment as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=244340427&amp;resource_type=Comment&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F55821480-the-invisible-life-of-addie-larue">flag</a>    

  </div>  
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div id="comment_244820623" class="brown_comment">
  <div class="xhr_comment_photo">
    	<a alt="Veronica" href="/user/show/145193918-veronica"><img src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_25x33-ccd24e68f4773d33a41ce08c3a34892e.png" alt="U 25x33" /></a>
  </div>
  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/145193918-veronica">Veronica</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer12292371814719247374">I wholeheartedly agree with your review. This book was enjoyable and I appreciated several lines about the value and passing of time, sentiments on wh</span>
  <span id="freeText12292371814719247374" style="display:none">I wholeheartedly agree with your review. This book was enjoyable and I appreciated several lines about the value and passing of time, sentiments on what love means, etc, but it is an extremely light, sort of superficial “cozy” or “beach” read. I found a lot of faults with the things she was able to do or learn in the given time versus what she didn’t/wasn’t. She never manages to be financially stable enough to venture very far from where Luc places her, yet she somehow finds the time to learn so many languages and to master her life in so many ways. I suppose we are supposed to give her a pass based on how physical things seem to “vanish” from her life and she always seems to struggle just to survive at a certain level. However, in all her planting of “ideas”, she doesn’t seem very concerned with humanitarian concepts and, instead, only values the fine arts. I don’t really think this book is trying to be read at a deep level. I don’t think it asks or wants the reader to delve too deeply into it because the entire premise cracks upon any type of close speculation. It’s more like a prime time fantasy soap: fun, clever, enjoyable, and light. That is all. It’s a nice read but not something with lasting literary merit. I enjoyed it for what it is: a palette cleanser to enjoy between more substantial works.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12292371814719247374" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

    <br/>

    <span class="xhrCommentFooter greyText">
      Feb 07, 2022 03:58AM
