    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3808567271" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3808567271" />
    <a title="Bhavya {on hiatus till March}" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march"><img alt="Bhavya {on hiatus till March}" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611319656p2/128191325.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3808567271?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bhavya {on hiatus till March}" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bhavya {on hiatus till March}" href="/user/show/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march">Bhavya {on hiatus till March}</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9781004019441" href="/book/show/55762354-the-invisible-life-of-addie-larue">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=4-5-stars">4-5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=4-stars">4-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=cover-appreciation">cover-appreciation</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=adult-fantasy">adult-fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=slow-burn">slow-burn</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=reviewed-2021">reviewed-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=love-triangle">love-triangle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=read-audiobook">read-audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128191325-bhavya-on-hiatus-till-march?shelf=read-audiobook-2021">read-audiobook-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3808567271" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10302377651725902762"><blockquote> <b> <i>“Because time is cruel to all, and crueler still to artists. Because visions weakens, and voices wither, and talent fades.... Because happiness is brief, and history is lasting, and in the end... everyone wants to be remembered.” </i></b>
</blockquote>  <br/><br/><b>~ Rating- 4 stars ~ <br/><br/><i>(<a href='https://booktriggerwarnings.com/index.php?title=The_Invisible_Life_of_Addie_LaRue_by_V.E._Schwab' rel='nofollow noopener'>Content/ Trigger Warnings</a>)</i><br/><br/>-Mention of some of these in the review- </b><br/><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/50623864.The_Invisible_Life_of_Addie_LaRue' title='The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue by V.E. Schwab' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue</a> by <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7168230.V_E__Schwab' title='V.E. Schwab' rel='nofollow noopener'>V.E. Schwab</a> is an extremely popular book. It is also very different from my preferred genre of reading, so this experience was unique for me</span>
  <span id="freeText10302377651725902762" style="display:none"><blockquote> <b> <i>“Because time is cruel to all, and crueler still to artists. Because visions weakens, and voices wither, and talent fades.... Because happiness is brief, and history is lasting, and in the end... everyone wants to be remembered.” </i></b>
</blockquote>  <br><br><b>~ Rating- 4 stars ~ <br><br><i>(<a href="https://booktriggerwarnings.com/index.php?title=The_Invisible_Life_of_Addie_LaRue_by_V.E._Schwab" rel="nofollow noopener">Content/ Trigger Warnings</a>)</i><br><br>-Mention of some of these in the review- </b><br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/50623864.The_Invisible_Life_of_Addie_LaRue" title="The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue by V.E. Schwab" rel="nofollow noopener">The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7168230.V_E__Schwab" title="V.E. Schwab" rel="nofollow noopener">V.E. Schwab</a> is an extremely popular book. It is also very different from my preferred genre of reading, so this experience was unique for me. I enjoyed the book a lot, and fortunately I was not completely disappointed in it. <br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1607393103ra/30489126.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>However, I still have several issues with it.<br><br><b>➼The plot </b><br><br>Addie LaRue makes a bargain to live forever. A bargain to be immortal. But she is also cursed to be forgotten. Cursed to never be remembered.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“Being forgotten, she thinks, is a bit like going mad. You begin to wonder what is real, if you are real. After all, how can a thing be real if it cannot be remembered?” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>For 300 years she has lived this curse, moving from places to places and learning new things. Meeting new people and exploring the world.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“But this is how you walk to the end of the world. This is how you live forever. Here is one day, and here is the next, and the next, and you take what you can, savor every stolen second, cling to every moment, until it’s gone.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>But Addie wants to leave a mark in this world. She wants to be remembered. She wants to live.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“If a person cannot leave a mark, do they exist?” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>One day, someone remembers her and Addie’s whole life changes.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“I remember you.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><br>The plot of the book was engaging, and I enjoyed reading it. There is a constant repetition of how lonely Addie is, but I think it is done for us to sympathise with her character. <br><br><blockquote> <i>“Live long enough, and you learn how to read a person. To ease them open like a book, some passages underlined and others hidden between the lines.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>There weren’t any major plot twists in the book, but it was still interesting. I personally liked the ending, but I feel that instead of concluding everything there are still several loose ends left which weren’t tied. <br><br><blockquote> <i>“What is a person without a mark?” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>This is also very romance focused, and I do feel that it had a lot more potential. It could have been a very powerful book which explored the experiences of someone who has lived for 300 years and shown how we humans have evolved with time. However, this part of the book wasn’t explored at all.<br><br>This book is a standalone, but there is a possibility it might become a series in the future due to the ending. But I enjoyed the rest of the book regardless.<br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997402.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br><b>➼The world </b><br><br>This book is technically set in France, but we explore a lot of other places like Europe, Germany. I enjoyed seeing these glimpses into Addie’s past but this is one of the major issues I had with this book.<br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997406.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Addie has lived for 300 years, yet she has only explored 3 continents. Even the languages she knows can be counted on fingers. Addie’s personally is shown to be curious, in fact the reason she wanted to live forever in the first place was to see the world.<br><br>Why hasn’t Addie seen more countries, cities, even villages? I think it goes against everything that we know of Addie’s personality not to explore the rest of the world. <br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3729262325?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">Joel Rochester’s review </a> and <a href="https://youtu.be/6BmdcNOBSNo" rel="nofollow noopener"> Cindy Pham’s video </a> do a much better job at explaining and expanding my point.<br><br>Addie touches on her experiences of war, but we don’t get much details from her regarding it. I understand why that was the case, but I think it would have been interesting to explore Addie’s feelings and her experience more in detail.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“The old gods may be great, but they are neither kind nor merciful. They are fickle, unsteady as moonlight on water, or shadows in a storm. If you insist on calling them, take heed: be careful what you ask for, be willing to pay the price. And no matter how desperate or dire, never pray to the gods that answer after dark.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>In this world, there happen to be new Gods, and old Gods.<br><br>We know that The Darkness was the one who cursed Addie, but we hardly get any details on how exactly this system works. We get to know some details about the concept of ‘taking a soul’ and the rules and regulations regarding it, but I would have loved to see it more in detail.<br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997399.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I did find the few places we saw interesting and I loved reading about Addie’s past.<br><br><b>➼The writing </b><br><br><blockquote> <i> They say people are like snowflakes, each one unique, but I think they're more like skies. Some are cloudy, some are stormy, some are clear, but no two are ever quite the same. </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>The writing of this book was absolutely beautiful. I enjoyed every bit of it.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“Books, she has found, are a way to live a thousand lives—or to find strength in a very long one.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997403.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>It is quite slow paced though, and there is a constant use of telling instead of showing. But I still loved the writing.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“Memories are stiff, but thoughts are freer things. They throw out roots, they spread and tangle, and come untethered from their source. They are clever, and stubborn, and perhaps--perhaps--they are in reach.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><b>➼The characters </b><br><br><b>
  <u>➡Addie </u>
</b><br><br><blockquote> <i> “I do not want to marry. I do not want to belong to someone else. I do not want to belong to anyone but myself. I want to be free. Free to live, and to find my own way, to love, or to be alone, but at least it is my choice, and I am so tired of not having choices, so scared of the years rushing past beneath my feet. I do not want to die as I've lived, which is no life at all.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>Addie is a curious person, and we can see that through her story. She loves to learn new things. I liked her as a character and I felt bad for what she had to endure.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“But a life without art, without wonder, without beautiful things—she would go mad. She has gone mad.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>But I didn’t like the fact that throughout a course of 300 years, Addie’s personally never changes.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“Do you think a life has any value if one doesn’t leave some mark upon the world?” </i>
</blockquote>  <br><br>Addie isn’t ever remembered by anyone, which means she can steal. She uses this to her benefit and it’s also her only way at survival. I liked this moral greyness to her character, but if she does steal she could use this to help others in need as well.<br><br>But we don’t see her caring for anyone but herself, and though I don’t mind a selfish character, does she really never change in 300 years? Doesn’t she question her thinking and ponder about change?<br><br>What I mean to say is, in 300 years Addie LaRue doesn’t change. <br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997400.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><blockquote> <i> No matter how many times she walks these blocks, no matter how many hours, or days, or years she spends learning the contours of New York, as soon as she turns her back it seems to shift again, reassemble. Buildings go up and come down, businesses open and close, people arrive and depart and the deck shuffles itself again and again and again. </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>The entire world changes, but Addie doesn’t. She’s still the same person. Her thinking is still the same. <br><br>I think that circumstances mould people, and if Addie has lived for so long wouldn’t something about her change?<br><br>This could have been an excellent way of showing how people change with time, but this factor was never explored in the book.<br><br>I did like her character, but I still felt that there was so much more potential to Addie LaRue that we never get to see.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“And there in the dark, he asks if it was really worth it.<br>Were the instants of joy worth the stretches of sorrow?<br>Were the moments of beauty worth the year of pain?<br>And she turns her head, and looks at him, and says 'Always.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><b>
  <u>➡The Darkness </u>
</b> <br><br><blockquote> <i>“The vexing thing about time,” he says, “is that it’s never enough. Perhaps a decade too short, perhaps a moment. But a life always ends too soon.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>The Darkness or Luc, is the main villain of the book. He is the one who curses Addie and gives her a life of immortality at the cost of being forgotten.<br><br>I personally didn’t find him as a villain and saw him more as a morally grey character. <br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997405.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I liked him and he is my favourite character of this book. His character arc was complex and I feel there is a lot more to him than we got to see. I would have liked to see more of his character.<br><br><blockquote> <i> “I am stronger than your god and older than your devil. I am the darkness between stars, and the roots beneath the earth. I am promise, and potential, and when it comes to playing games, I divine the rules, I set the pieces, and I choose when to play.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><b> <u>➡Henry </u></b> <br><br><blockquote> <i>“I remember seeing that picture and realizing that photographs weren’t real. There’s no context, just the illusion that you’re showing a snapshot of a life, but life isn’t snapshots, it’s fluid. So photos are like fictions. I loved that about them. Everyone thinks photography is truth, but it’s just a very convincing lie.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br>I found Henry to be an ok character. I don’t have any strong emotions for him, but he definitely got more interesting when his backstory was explored.<br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997401.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I felt that he was just there in the story for the sake of it, and I didn’t like that so much.<br><br><blockquote> <i>“They teach you growing up that you are only one thing at a time—angry, lonely, content—but he’s never found that to be true. He is a dozen things at once. He is lost and scared and grateful, he is sorry and happy and afraid.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><b>➼The romance </b><br><br>I do not ship Addie with anyone. I did not like Addie with Henry or The Darkness. In my opinion, she's better off not ending with anyone, but I ship her more with The Darkness over Henry. <br><br><blockquote> <i>“It is easy to be honest when there are no wrong words, because the words don't stick. When whatever you say belongs to only you.” </i>
</blockquote> <br><br><b>➼Audiobook Comments </b><br><br>The audiobook narration was absolutely excellent and if you are comfortable with the format and have access to the audiobook, I would recommend you to read it.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1545586749ra/26797020.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The narration was very impactful and I don’t think I would have felt so connected with Addie’s story if I had read the copy.<br><br><br><b>➼Final thoughts </b><br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/50623864.The_Invisible_Life_of_Addie_LaRue" title="The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue by V.E. Schwab" rel="nofollow noopener">The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue</a> is an engaging book and it kept me invested. This book is not YA though, and I would not recommend the book to anyone under 14, as I feel this deals with much more mature content. Despite my issues with the book, it was a very fun and emotional read. I enjoyed it thoroughly.<br><br><blockquote> <i><b><br><br>“And when she does look up, her gaze always goes to the edge of town.<br>"A dreamer," scorns her mother.<br>"A dreamer," mourns her father.<br>"A dreamer," warns Estele.<br>Still, it does not seem such a bad word.<br>Until Adeline wakes up.” </b></i>
</blockquote> <br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1615483763ra/30997404.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br><br><i>BOTM for the group <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/group/show/1149330-the-one-who-reads-several-books" rel="nofollow noopener">The one who reads several books</a>.<br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/21886350-the-invisible-life-of-addie-larue--march-2021?comment=227454872&amp;page=2#comment_227454872" rel="nofollow noopener">Here</a> is the thread. (Note- the thread has spoilers, do not click if you haven't read the book)</i><br><br><i>
  <b>
    <u>Review written on 11th March, 2021.</u>
  </b>
</i><br><br><b> DISCLAIMER- </b> All opinions on books I’ve read and reviewed are my own, and are with no intention to offend anyone. If you feel offended by my reviews, let me know how I can fix it. <br><br><u> How I Rate-</u><br>1 star- Hardly liked anything/ was disappointed<br>2 star- Had potential but did not deliver/ was disappointed<br>3 stars- Was ok but could have been better/ was average / Enjoyed a lot but something was missing<br>4 stars- Loved a lot but something was missing<br>5 stars- Loved it/ new favourite <br><br>………………………………….………<br><br>Pre review thoughts<br><br>4 stars.<br>Review to come.<br><br>Well here are my thoughts for now. I’ll write a detailed review later.<br><br>So I loved the writing. Enjoyed it a lot.<br>But one issue I had with that was the telling vs showing. <br><br>I loved the flashback scenes a lot though.<br>But the issue I has was that Addie has lived for 300 years, yet in all this time there are hardly 5-6 places explored. Even the languages she knows can be counted in fingers.<br>If she’s lived for so long, wouldn’t she have wanted to learn more? Explore more? Read more?<br><br>Another thing is addie’s personally.<br>She’s lived for so long, yet her personality doesn’t change at all. 300 years, and no change? That’s a bit hard to believe as I feel people keep changing. Circumstances mould people, and after all that addie been through I expected some change in her way of thinking.<br><br>So this is why this book is not a five star for me.<br>I loved it, enjoyed it but it’s not a five star.<br>But this is a standalone, so I will cut it some slack. It’s just that I would have liked to see these points explored more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10302377651725902762" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
